<subSubSection id="B835D19CB9BC2A3E2100DA057EB33C31" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="EDA3F94BB14E88D3BCA0A8D1543AE5E5" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4EF357B8290D48E8FE3AE08A21CA90F8" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">OL:OH = 1.55-1.75; OH:OT = 4.0-5.0. Rostrum length 37-45% of OL. Ventral rim of ostium shallow and fading, and ostium relatively narrow; OsH:CaH = 1.25-1.6.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8BE33175D747D8A47CBF17738C4B7DE3" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" type="description">
<paragraph id="23174A83F93EB85FFC9CA8832F97E88C" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="47E0C6EF86CACF4AF836C6ABAB1D15BA" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">Slender, thin otoliths up to 3.25 mm in length (holotype 2.65 mm). Ventral rim relatively shallow, regularly curved, deepest at or behind middle, and smooth to irregularly undulating. Rostrum very long, nearly half of otolith length. Dorsal rim behind ostial opening short, moderately elevated, broad and irregularly undulating. Posterior rim broadly rounded.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="25C75172894B2A4913DF63F32CA3A299" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">Inner face very slightly bent with distinctly supramedian sulcus. Ostium long, not expanding backward from rostrum and antirostral notch, about as long as cauda but separation poorly defined. Ventral margin of ostium indistinct, gradual, and shallow, resulting in relatively narrow ostium. Cauda very slightly flexed, terminating close to posterior tip of otolith. Dorsal depression very small, restricted to position above anterior part of cauda. No ventral furrow. Outer face flat to slightly concave with particularly thin and delicate rostrum, smooth dorsally and few indistinct furrows ventrally. Shallow umbo positioned near dorsal rim opposite to dorsal field of inner face.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="1FDD9AFF789F6478B97A12E2771AA247" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="A8190761493DBBFCBA0C9DFA6FBDCCBE" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D13C042A66CEC1067E040E2D8FDD61A5" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">
<taxonomicName id="169B368E9EC74502801AE902B5F7A965" authorityName="Schwarzhans &amp; Keupp" authorityYear="2022" class="Actinopterygii" family="Leptolepididae" genus="Leptolepis" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Leptolepis buttenheimensis" order="Elopiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" rank="species" species="buttenheimensis">
<emphasis id="CBFF18A32EC3A040FEF83E9C361B68CC" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">Leptolepis buttenheimensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is readily recognized by its elongated shape, extremely long rostrum, and very thin and delicate structure. However, a few morphologically transitional specimens exist with 
<taxonomicName id="B9ABA29EC8F630608F9DA91692A9BDFE" class="Actinopterygii" genus="L." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="L. normandica" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="normandica">
<emphasis id="51847199134C1BE0DD7FD363F59E71DF" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">L. normandica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in specimens smaller than about 2.2 mm in length, which are not considered to be fully morphologically developed. Another distinctive feature is the shallow and fading lower margin of the ostium as seen in figures 1a, 2, 3a, 4a, 5 and 7a on Plate 
<figureCitation id="84FE2F3B8663AA3BCB73087500E6DAF5" captionStart="Plate 2" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Plate 2. Otoliths of Leptolepis buttenheimensis and L. steberae. figs 1 - 7 Leptolepis buttenheimensis sp. nov. from the late Pliensbachian of Buttenheim; 1: holotype SNSB-BSPG 2022 IV 4, EPH horizon; 2 - 7: paratypes SNSB-BSPG 2022 IV 5 - 6; 2 - 5, 7: EPH horizon; 6: Apyrenum subzone. figs 8 - 12: Leptolepis steberae sp. nov. from the Pliensbachian of Buttenheim, EPH horizon; 8: holotype SNSB-BSPG 2022 IV 13; 9 - 12: paratypes SNSB-BSPG 2022 IV 14." figureDoi="10.3897/zitteliana.96.81737.plate2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671632" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">2</figureCitation>
. This development somewhat resembles otoliths of 
<taxonomicName id="046981263AFE47153E65D1632F4BB87C" baseAuthorityName="Weiler" baseAuthorityYear="1954" genus="Leptoelops" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Leptoelops rhenanus" order="Elopiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" rank="species" species="rhenanus">
<emphasis id="19C403C653DD6C93FB77C69A0E6BD935" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">Leptoelops rhenanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see below) where the lower margin of the ostium has become completely flattened and is level with the ventral margin of the cauda.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="120AB3D363C2A52BE0F35FFB1B1D08D8" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">
<taxonomicName id="78A9BCB10B838C4D284CD660AED094BD" authorityName="Schwarzhans &amp; Keupp" authorityYear="2022" class="Actinopterygii" family="Leptolepididae" genus="Leptolepis" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Leptolepis buttenheimensis" order="Elopiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" rank="species" species="buttenheimensis">
<emphasis id="DFA2A577598F1D0170E26B1D87E2184D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">Leptolepis buttenheimensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known only from the upper Pliensbachian of the type locality where it represents the second most common species.
</paragraph>
<caption id="4DE9DE7E85427DFC4AD93CE5AEAEE50A" doi="10.3897/zitteliana.96.81737.plate2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671632" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" start="Plate 2" startId="F4">
<paragraph id="FA4BEAFB78D696D147730D1A14573D9E" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis id="9B4FB2507396FA282CE42B09402D4F3E" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">Plate 2.</emphasis>
Otoliths of 
<taxonomicName id="42371BA480EDABEBFAE34E9771FBBC49" authorityName="Schwarzhans &amp; Keupp" authorityYear="2022" class="Actinopterygii" family="Leptolepididae" genus="Leptolepis" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Leptolepis buttenheimensis" order="Elopiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" rank="species" species="buttenheimensis">
<emphasis id="3E601F779CDD027FEE794227C038E4B8" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">Leptolepis buttenheimensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="05611FB5FDA572F570FB80299A921108" class="Actinopterygii" genus="L." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="L. steberae" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="steberae">
<emphasis id="382BE69A5D179314C0BF21130062828C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">L. steberae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<emphasis id="5B2004F03B7AEE14BAE2F8949A5D9F8D" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">figs 1-7</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="8A736F1FB9D5B99A0D1E5435569C0FA0" authorityName="Schwarzhans &amp; Keupp" authorityYear="2022" class="Actinopterygii" family="Leptolepididae" genus="Leptolepis" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Leptolepis buttenheimensis" order="Elopiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" rank="species" species="buttenheimensis">
<emphasis id="FF728A1BBCD436BD602463B5D5BEDB08" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">Leptolepis buttenheimensis</emphasis>
